04879nam a22007455i 9780231541664DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315416647 a10.7312/keoh178022doi  a(DE-B1597)479866  a(OCoLC)979776926  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHG101b.K46 2016eb 7aBUS0990002bisacsh04a174/.42231 aKeohane, Georgia Levenson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCapital and the Common Good :bHow Innovative Finance Is Tackling the World's Most Urgent Problems /cGeorgia Levenson Keohane. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b12 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Business School Publishing00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Innovative Finance and the Visible Hand -- tREDD Forests, Green Bonds, and the Price of Carbon -- t2. Health: Medicine for Market Failure -- t3. Financial Inclusion and Access to Capital -- t4. Toward a New Disaster Finance: Redefining Risk, Response, and Resilience -- t5. Innovative Finance in Communities Across the United States -- tConclusion: Financing the Future: The Lessons of Innovative Finance and the TIES That Bind -- tEpilogue: The Road Ahead -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite social and economic advances around the world, poverty and disease persist, exacerbated by the mounting challenges of climate change, natural disasters, political conflict, mass migration, and economic inequality. While governments commit to addressing these challenges, traditional public and philanthropic dollars are not enough. Here, innovative finance has shown a way forward: by borrowing techniques from the world of finance, we can raise capital for social investments today. Innovative finance has provided polio vaccines to children in the DRC, crop insurance to farmers in India, pay-as-you-go solar electricity to Kenyans, and affordable housing and transportation to New Yorkers. It has helped governmental, commercial, and philanthropic resources meet the needs of the poor and underserved and build a more sustainable and inclusive prosperity. Capital and the Common Good shows how market failure in one context can be solved with market solutions from another: an expert in securitization bundles future development aid into bonds to pay for vaccines today; an entrepreneur turns a mobile phone into an array of financial services for the unbanked; and policy makers adapt pay-for-success models from the world of infrastructure to human services like early childhood education, maternal health, and job training. Revisiting the successes and missteps of these efforts, Georgia Levenson Keohane argues that innovative finance is as much about incentives and sound decision-making as it is about money. When it works, innovative finance gives us the tools, motivation, and security to invest in our shared future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspects. 0aFinancexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aFinancexSocial aspects. 0aSocial responsibility of business. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Environmental Economics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/keoh1780240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231541664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231541664/original  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMAL